stinian Refugee Reparations -- t13. Repairing Colonial Symmetry: Algerian Archive Restitution As Reparation for Crimes of Colonialism? -- t14. The Romani Genocide During the Holocaust: Resistance and Restitution -- tPART IV. WAYS FORWARD FOR REPARATIONS -- t15. The Roma Case for Reparations -- t16. What Justice for Starvation Crimes? -- t17. Stopping the Crimes While Repairing the Victims: Personal Reflections of a Global Prosecutor -- tPostscript -- tNotes -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this sweeping international perspective on reparations, Time for Reparations makes the case that past state injustice—be it slavery or colonization, forced sterilization or widespread atrocities—has enduring consequences that generate ongoing harm, which needs to be addressed as a matter of justice and equity.Time for Reparations provides a wealth of detailed and diverse examples of state injustice, from enslavement of African Americans in the United States and Roma in Romania, to colonial exploitation and brutality in Guatemala, Algeria, Indonesia, Jamaica, and Guadeloupe. From many vantage points, contributing authors discuss different reparative strategies and the impact they would have on the lives of survivor or descent communities.One of the strengths of this book is its interdisciplinary perspective—contributors are historians, anthropologists, human rights lawyers, sociologists, and political scientists. Many of the authors are both scholars and advocates, actively involved in one capacity or another in the struggles for reparations they describe. The book therefore has a broad and inclusive scope, aided by an accessible and cogent writing style. It appeals to scholars, students, advocates and others concerned about addressing some of the most profound and enduring injustices of our time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aReparations for historical injusticesvCase studies. 0aReparations for historical injustices. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Human Rights.2bisacsh  aColombian.  aColonization.  aIndigenous Guatemalan women.  aMau Mau.  aNakba.  aPalestinian refugees.  aReparations.  aRomani genocide.  aSlavery.  aStarvation crimes.  astructural racism.1 aBassett, Mary T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeckles, Sir Hilary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBhabha, Jacqueline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBhabha, Jacqueline, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aConley, Bridget, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElkins, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElkins, Caroline, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFischbach, Michael R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFord, Aileen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrance, Mireille Fanon Mendes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrivet, Joanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHancock, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aImmler, Nicole L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Douglas A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKhalidi, Rashid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatache, Margareta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatache, Margareta, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMiles, Tiya, econtributor.4ctb4htt